The formatting is irrelevant.  `Date`, like most date/time classes `Date` is a container for the amount of time which has passed since a given point in time (in this case, the Unix Epoch).

The result of `Date#toString` should only be used for debug purposes and it&#39;s result could change depending on localisation and time zone.

You should also beware that `Date` DOES NOT carry any formatting information, again, it&#39;s output should purely be considered for debugging only, in almost all other cases, use a formatter instead, that&#39;s why they exist.

If we take some time to &quot;fix&quot; your code (so it will run) and output the values...

    SimpleDateFormat dateFormat = new SimpleDateFormat(&quot;yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSS&quot;);

    Date compDate = dateFormat.parse(&quot;2023-07-14 01:22:14.077&quot;);
    Date newDate = dateFormat.parse(&quot;2023-07-13 01:22:14.077&quot;);

    System.out.println(&quot;   compDate = &quot; + dateFormat.format(compDate) + &quot; // Formatted&quot;);
    System.out.println(&quot;   compDate = &quot; + compDate);
    System.out.println(&quot;    newDate = &quot; + dateFormat.format(newDate) + &quot; // Formatted&quot;);
    System.out.println(&quot;    newDate = &quot; + newDate);

    Calendar cal = Calendar.getInstance();
    cal.setTime(newDate);
    cal.add(Calendar.HOUR_OF_DAY, 12);
    newDate = cal.getTime();

    System.out.println(&quot;new newDate = &quot; + dateFormat.format(newDate) + &quot; // Formatted&quot;);
    System.out.println(&quot;new newDate = &quot; + newDate);

    System.out.println(&quot;Compare = &quot; + compDate.after(newDate));

We end up with something like... 

       compDate = 2023-07-14 01:22:14.077 // Formatted
       compDate = Fri Jul 14 01:22:14 AEST 2023
        newDate = 2023-07-13 01:22:14.077 // Formatted
        newDate = Thu Jul 13 01:22:14 AEST 2023
    new newDate = 2023-07-13 13:22:14.077 // Formatted
    new newDate = Thu Jul 13 13:22:14 AEST 2023
    Compare = true

As you can clearly see, the value of `Date` doesn&#39;t change, but we can affect the output through the formatter.

# Modern approach...

Let&#39;s update the code to remove the reliance on deprecated functionality and make use of the newer `java.time.*` APIs, which you should be using instead.

    DateTimeFormatter formatter = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(&quot;yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSS&quot;);
    LocalDateTime compDate = LocalDateTime.parse(
            &quot;2023-07-14 01:22:14.077&quot;,
            formatter
    );
    LocalDateTime newDate = LocalDateTime.parse(
            &quot;2023-07-13 01:22:14.077&quot;,
            formatter
    );

    System.out.println(&quot;compDate = &quot; + compDate);
    System.out.println(&quot;compDate = &quot; + formatter.format(compDate) + &quot; // Formatted&quot;);
    System.out.println(&quot; newDate = &quot; + newDate);
    System.out.println(&quot; newDate = &quot; + formatter.format(newDate) + &quot; // Formatted&quot;);

    newDate = newDate.plusHours(12);

    System.out.println(&quot; newDate = &quot; + newDate);
    System.out.println(&quot; newDate = &quot; + formatter.format(newDate) + &quot; // Formatted&quot;);

    System.out.println(&quot;Compare = &quot; + compDate.isAfter(newDate));

Which outputs...

    compDate = 2023-07-14T01:22:14.077
    compDate = 2023-07-14 01:22:14.077 // Formatted
     newDate = 2023-07-13T01:22:14.077
     newDate = 2023-07-13 01:22:14.077 // Formatted
     newDate = 2023-07-13T13:22:14.077
     newDate = 2023-07-13 13:22:14.077 // Formatted
    Compare = true

Again, the format is irrelevant.  Get your values from `String` (and make use of ISO standard formats to do it) to `LocalDate`/`LocalDateTime` (or the `Zoned` variants) and manipulate them as needed, you only need care about the format when it needs to be presented to the user.

