&gt; Try printing the value of total for generateCombinations(15, 2). Then learn about integer overflow.  
tgdavies

Thank you for the insight, that is what this site is here for. I know about overflow which is why I facepalmed to the roof. For those that do not know, hitting the value of 2^32 with integers will send you into the negatives. While this is not a permanent fix -- BigInteger is preferable for extreme edge cases -- here lies the problem:

```java
public static int factorial(int n)
    return n * ((n &gt; 1) ? factorial(n - 1) : n);
}
```
and here is a simple solution:
```java
public static double factorial(double n)
    return n * ((n &gt; 1) ? factorial(n - 1) : n);
}
```

**Edit for a more detailed solution**
```java
// exact decimal values
public static BigInteger factorial(BigInteger n) {
    return (n.compareTo(BigDecimal.ONE) &lt;= 0)
            ? BigInteger.ONE
            : n.multiply(factorial(n.subtract(BigInteger.ONE)));
}

// finding the number of combinations given the algorithm
public static long total(int n, int k) {
    if (n == 0 || k == 0 || n &lt; k)
        return 0;
    if (n == k)
        return 1;
    BigInteger factorial = factorial(BigInteger.valueOf(n))
            .divide(factorial(BigInteger.valueOf(k))
                    .multiply(factorial(BigInteger.valueOf(n - k))));
    return factorial.longValue();
}
```
This states that BigInteger `n` will be divided by the product of `factorial(n - 1)` and `factorial(n - k)` where `n` is the number of elements and `k` is the size of each list generated

